#. type: Title =====
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Resource Management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Resource Management* involves all the necessary steps to define what is being protected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/resource-mgmt-process.png[alt=\"Resource Management Overview\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "First, you need to specify {project_name} what are you looking to protect, which usually represents a web application or a set of one or more services. For more information on resource servers see <<_overview_terminology, Terminology>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Resource servers are managed using the {project_name} Administration Console. There you can enable any registered client application as a resource server and start managing the resources and scopes you want to protect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/rs-r-scopes.png[alt=\"Resource Server Overview\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "A resource can be a web page, a RESTFul resource, a file in your file system, an EJB, and so on. They can represent a group of resources (just like a Class in Java) or they can represent a single and specific resource.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "For instance, you might have a _Bank Account_ resource that represents all banking accounts and use it to define the authorization policies that are common to all banking accounts. However, you might want to define specific policies for _Alice Account_ (a resource instance that belongs to a customer), where only the owner is allowed to access some information or perform an operation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "Resources can be managed using the {project_name} Administration Console or the <<_service_protection_api, Protection API>>. In the latter case, resource servers are able to manage their resources remotely.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "Scopes usually represent the actions that can be performed on a resource, but they are not limited to that. You can also use scopes to represent one or more attributes within a resource.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Permission and Policy Management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have defined your resource server and all the resources you want to protect, you must set up permissions and policies.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "This process involves all the necessary steps to actually define the security and access requirements that govern your resources.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:65
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/policy-mgmt-process.png[alt=\"Permission and Policy Management Overview\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "Policies define the conditions that must be satisfied to access or perform operations on something (resource or scope), but they are not tied to what they are protecting. They are generic and can be reused to build permissions or even more complex policies.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "For instance,to allow access to a group of resources only for users granted with a role \"User Premium,\"\" you can use RBAC (Role-based Access Control).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "{project_name} provides a few built-in policy types (and their respective policy providers) covering the most common access control mechanisms. You can even create policies based on rules written using JavaScript or JBoss Drools.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have your policies defined, you can start defining your permissions. Permissions are coupled with the resource they are protecting. Here you specify\n"
"what you want to protect (resource or scope) and the policies that must be satisfied to grant or deny permission.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "Policy Enforcement"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Policy Enforcement* involves the necessary steps to actually enforce authorization decisions to a resource server. This is achieved by enabling a *Policy Enforcement Point* or PEP at the resource server that is capable of communicating with the authorization server, ask for authorization data and control access to protected resources based on the decisions and permissions returned by the server.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "{project_name} provides some built-in <<_enforcer_overview, Policy Enforcers>> implementations that you can use to protect your applications depending on the platform they are running on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:84
#: source/authorization_services/topics/service/overview.adoc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Authorization Services"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "Authorization services consist of the following RESTFul APIs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Protection API*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Authorization API*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Entitlement API*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each of these services provides a specific API covering the different steps involved in the authorization process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:94
#: source/authorization_services/topics/service/protection/protection-api.adoc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Protection API"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:99
#, no-wrap
msgid "The *Protection API* is a https://kantarainitiative.org/confluence/display/uma/UMA+1.0+Core+Protocol[UMA-compliant] endpoint providing a small set of operations\n"
"for resource servers to help them manage their resources and scopes. Only resource servers are allowed to access this API, which also requires a\n"
"*uma_protection* scope.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:101
#, no-wrap
msgid "The operations provided by the Protection API can be organized in two main groups:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "** Create Resource\n"
"** Delete Resource\n"
"** Find by Id\n"
"** Find All\n"
"** Find with filters (for example, search by name, type, or URI)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Permission Management*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "** Issue Permission Tickets\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, Remote Resource Management is enabled. You can change that using the {project_name} Administration Console and only allow resource management through the console.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "When using the UMA protocol, the issuance of Permission Tickets by the Protection API is an important part of the whole authorization process. As described in a subsequent section, they represent the permissions being requested by the client and that are sent to the server to obtain a final token with all permissions granted during the evaluation of the permissions and policies associated with the resources and scopes being requested.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:117
#, no-wrap
msgid "For more information, see <<_service_protection_api, Protection API>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:118
#: source/authorization_services/topics/service/authorization/authorization-api.adoc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Authorization API"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:121
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Authorization API is also a https://kantarainitiative.org/confluence/display/uma/UMA+1.0+Core+Protocol[UMA-compliant] endpoint providing a single operation that exchanges an Access Token and <<_overview_terminology_permission_ticket, Permission Ticket>> with a Requesting Party Token (RPT).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "The RPT contains all permissions granted to a client and can be used to call a resource server to get access to its protected resources.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:126
#, no-wrap
msgid "When requesting an RPT you can also provide a previously issued RPT. In this case, the resulting RPT will consist of the union of the permissions from the previous RPT and the new ones\n"
"within a permission ticket.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:128
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/authz-calls.png[alt=\"Authorization API Overview\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:130
#, no-wrap
msgid "For more information, see <<_service_authorization_api, Authorization API>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:131
#: source/authorization_services/topics/service/entitlement/entitlement-api.adoc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Entitlement API"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:134
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Entitlement API provides a 1-legged protocol to issue RPTs. Unlike the Authorization API, the Entitlement API only expects an access token.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "From this API you can obtain all the entitlements or permissions for a user (based on the resources managed by a given resource server) or just the entitlements for a set of\n"
"one or more resources.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/entitlement-calls.png[alt=\"Entitlement API Overview\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/authorization_services/topics/overview/architecture.adoc:141
#, no-wrap
msgid "For more information see <<_service_entitlement_api, Entitlement API>>.\n"
msgstr ""

